{
  "content": "2000 January In the US, America Online merges with Time Warner; and in the UK Greg Dyke becomes 13th BBC director general, ending the eight-year John Birt era. Bolstered by a generous licence fee settlement, Dyke moves main news from 9pm to the 10pm slot vacated by ITV and allocates \u00a3115m extra a year to BBC1, a 15% increase. May Radio Authority fines Virgin \u00a375,000 for Chris Evans's on-air endorsement of Ken Livingstone as London mayoral candidate. July Big Brother ushers in a decade of reality entertainment shows after becoming an instant hit for Channel 4 with the final peaking at 9.9 million. It heralds a TV-led internet age, with live streaming. And also ensures the rise of Heat magazine, relaunched earlier in the year by its new editor, Mark Frith. BSkyB ends the year with 4.6 million subscribers while Carlton and Granada's challenger ONdigital has 1 million. Almost a third of the population have multi-channel TV. 2001 January E4 launches as a pay channel, with rights to Friends and ER. April Cond\u00e9 Nast launches Glamour magazine in pioneering \"handbag\" size, and it swiftly becomes the top monthly. September 9/11 changes everything. The dotcom bubble bursts, destroying the value of companies such as AOL, checking Yahoo's rise, and denting confidence in online investments. UK TV advertising collapses by 10%. Escapism rules \u2013 Pop Idol launches on ITV in October, making a star of Simon Cowell, and starting a global phenomenon of the rise of \"shiny floor\" entertainment. The revolutionary Sky+ service launches. Access Radio pilot experiments pave the way to a rapid spread of community radio. 2002 March ITV Digital collapses, losing Carlton and Granada \u00a31.2bn. Greg Dyke's consortium later recycles the digital proposition as Freeview, and Granada and Carlton reject opportunity to join it. Mark Thompson joins C4 as chief executive and, in an uncertain climate, opens talks with Channel Five on merger. The free Metro newspaper moves into profit. Robert Thomson replaces Peter Stothard as Times editor and the BBC presses ahead with bbc.co.uk website expansion. 2003 July The communications act creates one powerful regulator, Ofcom. The act allows US media companies to own broadcasters such as ITV, though European companies cannot own US networks. A new code of conduct hands programme rights to independent producers from broadcasters, which, together with the BBC \"Window of Creative Competition\", leads to a five-year boom in business. May Andrew Gilligan broadcasts at 6am on Radio 4 about \"sexed-up\" WMD documents. October Granada and Carlton are given permission, by the Competition Commission, to merge. The Independent turns from broadsheet to tabloid, with views on the front page, in a bid to rescue circulation, and the Financial Times starts charging for its website. 2004 January the Hutton report is highly critical of the BBC editorial system, prompting the departure of the chairman, Gavyn Davies, and Dyke. Michael Grade is appointed chairman in April and soon after Mark Thompson becomes director general. Luke Johnson is Ofcom's maverick choice as C4 chairman and he selects Andy Duncan, an architect of Freeview, as chief executive. Talks with Five end and a campaign for public assistance starts. Broadband becomes more widely available and cheaper after Ofcom forces through local loop unbundling on BT, making the web 2.0 era affordable. May Piers Morgan is fired as Daily Mirror editor, after the paper's supposed photos of abuse of Iraqi prisoners are exposed as fakes; radio groups GWR and Capital announce they are to merge to form GCap \u2013 consolidation is favoured by Ofcom. July The Barclay brothers buy Telegraph newspapers for \u00a3655m from Conrad Black. Murdoch MacLennan becomes chief executive and Will Lewis is hired as City editor, then handed the editorship. August Google 's IPO values it at $23bn. November The Times goes tabloid-only, after a spell of printing tabloid and broadsheet versions. 2005 February Channel 4's Jamie's School Dinners, a powerful social campaigning series, sparks a national debate and reform over food quality and diet. Nora Sands becomes a celebrity dinner lady. Grazia magazine is launched. May Arianna Huffington launches the Huffington Post, her news website and blog. July Thinkbox is launched to promote mass-market TV advertising, as social networking sites such as MySpace \u2013 bought by Rupert Murdoch in the same month for $580m \u2013 divert younger people. September The Guardian is relaunched in Berliner format. October ITV presses ahead with its 50th anniversary party at London's Guildhall, attended by the Queen. The broadcaster buys Friends Reunited for \u00a3120m. November Andrew Gowers is ousted as editor of the Financial Times and replaced by Lionel Barber. December The BBC starts nine ultra-local news pilots, to the consternation of the newspaper industry. The BBC Trust later pulls the service, and allocates \u00a368m to improving existing services. 2006 March John Micklethwait is appointed editor of the Economist, with the goal of bumping up circulation from 1m globally, which duly happens. Charles Allen launches cITV but cuts regional news, halves regional programmes, and shunts off afternoon slots on ITV. He leaves ITV by September amid shareholders' unrest over the weak share price. Greg Dyke leads a consortium of private equity bidders for ITV, at 135p a share. ITV directors reject the bid. BSkyB pounces, spending \u00a3920m on a 17.8% stake in ITV to block Virgin Media. News International launches the free London Paper and Associated responds with London Lite. Facebook becomes open to everyone over 13. October Google begins acquisitions by buying YouTube for $1.65bn. November Michael Grade abruptly resigns as chair of the BBC Trust. The BBC licence fee settlement includes a ringfenced digital switchover fund. 2007 January Grade joins ITV as executive chairman. His turnaround plan aims to boost production. Dawn Airey, director of global content, walks out six months later to return to Five. In the same month, Celebrity Big Brother is sullied by racism and bullying rows involving Shilpa Shetty and Jade Goody; and the BBC Trust replaces the governors, and then shuts down the online educational service Jam. March Twitter sees a surge in tweet numbers at the South by Southwest festival, and becomes a freestanding company the following month. April Facebook overtakes MySpace internationally in monthly unique users according to comScore. May Britain's Got Talent launches, attracting 11.6 million viewers and kicking off Paul Potts's singing career \u2013 Cowell has his second big hit. July In a year of outrage over phoneline fakery, premium-rated quiz scams and worse, Blue Peter gets its first-ever fine of \u00a350,000. Former Telegraph owner Conrad Black is fined and jailed for diverting company funds for personal use. August Rupert Murdoch pays $5bn to acquire Dow Jones and hence the Wall Street Journal. September The culture secretary, James Purnell, announces the Convergence Think Tank to prepare for new digital legislation. October BBC Worldwide buys Lonely Planet for \u00a3118m, provoking an outcry from rival publishers. Peter Fincham is ousted as BBC1 controller after doctored scenes of the Queen are used. Stephen Lambert of RDF, whose tape was to blame, resigns from RDF. Facebook is valued at $15bn when Microsoft takes a small stake. December Emap radio and magazines are sold to Bauer. 2008 January ITV reinstates News at Ten with Sir Trevor McDonald, but it struggles to reach its target of 3 million viewers. C4 cancels Celebrity Big Brother and Oneword digital radio channel is replaced by birdsong. March ITV's new-style dramas, The Palace and Moving Wallpaper/Echo Beach, flop and Simon Shaps is replaced by Fincham. April Roger Alton becomes the Independent's editor after quitting the Observer. May Jay Hunt becomes BBC1 controller and quickly revamps Countryfile into a Sunday night hit. GCap is fined \u00a31.1m for irregularities in competitions. July Max Mosley wins \u00a360,000 in damages against the News of the World for breaching his privacy over Nazi-themed spanking sessions. September Ofcom proposes divesting the BBC of some or all of BBC Worldwide, to assist C4, but has to back off. October The BBC is rocked by Sachsgate \u2013 broadcasts by Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand \u2013 which results in the resignation of Radio 2's controller, Lesley Douglas, and a review of editorial controls. C4 pulls out of digital radio. November Janice Hadlow becomes BBC2 controller and promises a wider range of culture and history, and no more programmes about Nazis. Paul Dacre, editor-in-chief of the Mail, attacks Justice Eady, who awarded Mosley the damages, for constructing a creeping privacy law under the umbrella of the Human Rights Act. 2009 The latest culture secretary, Stephen Carter, begins the year with a review of digital services. In unveiling his report six months later, he announces his own departure, leaving others to shepherd the proposals (a \u00a36 annual levy on phone lines to fund broadband rollout, as well as pilots for independently funded news consortia in three areas) through parliament. March ITV confirms cuts to its programme budget from \u00a31bn to \u00a3750m, and heavy redundancies and closures at its northern bases, Leeds and Manchester, and write-offs of \u00a32.7bn. Jade Goody's last days are shown on Living TV. June Criticised by the Public Accounts Committee, the BBC starts to implement a 25% cut to star pay as both the DG and the BBC Trust begin fierce opposition to any form of sharing the licence fee. Critics circle the trust, led by the opposition culture spokesman, Jeremy Hunt August BSkyB \u2013 which had marked its 20th anniversary in February \u2013 cements its power by announcing turnover of \u00a35.3bn, three times that of ITV, and subscribers approaching 10 million. With Freeview already in 10m homes, the decade will end with digital TV in 92% of households. The same month's MacTaggart lecture from James Murdoch, News Corp's Europe and Asia overlord, sees him attack Ofcom and the BBC. His assertion that \"the only reliable, durable, perpetual guarantor of independence is profit\" starts off industry debate about paying for content and the value of news and journalism. November ITV chooses Archie Norman as chairman, with Grade leaving, and by the following month the network is enjoying a ratings boom thanks largely to The X Factor. December AOL resumes life as an independent internet company as it completes its spinoff from Time Warner Inc, thus closing the book on one of the most disastrous business combinations in history. Additional reporting by John Dugdale",
  "title": "The decade that reality bit",
